## Build

Requires `arm-none-eabi-gcc` and CMake ≥ 3.24. The first configure fetches
[executorch]({{ "https://github.com/pytorch/executorch" }}) at the pinned tag `{{ executorch_tag }}`.

```bash
cmake -B build -DCMAKE_TOOLCHAIN_FILE=cmake/arm-none-eabi.cmake
cmake --build build
```

This produces:

- `lib{{ project_name }}.a` — the embedded program + `fitchip_run()` runner,
- `{{ project_name }}_example` — a reference executable (needs your linker
  script: add `-DFITCHIP_LINKER_SCRIPT=/path/to/your.ld`).

## Integrating into your firmware

FitChip is honest about what it generates: **this is not a complete STM32
firmware image.** You provide, typically from CubeMX or your BSP:

1. startup code + vector table + linker script for {{ target.display_name }},
2. clock/HAL initialization,
3. a `main()` that calls `fitchip_run()` (or link the example target).

Wire your sensor data into `fill_inputs()` in `main.cpp` and read results
via `method->get_output(i)`.

## Memory notes

- The activation pool is a single static buffer ({{ (arena_bytes / 1024) | round | int }} KB).
  {{ "Its size is exact — the ExecuTorch memory plan is baked into the .pte at export time, so unlike heuristic arenas there is no safety factor to trim." if arena_exact else "The .pte's memory plan could not be read at generation time (install `fitchip[executorch]` for exact numbers). If `load_method()` fails, raise `kActivationBytes`." }}
- Programs planned with multiple memory ids need one `Span` per id in
  `HierarchicalAllocator` — the runner covers the common single-arena case.
- `kMethodPoolBytes` ({{ (method_pool_bytes / 1024) | round | int }} KB) holds method metadata; raise it only if
  `load_method()` reports allocation failures with a sufficient activation pool.

## CMSIS-NN

`FITCHIP_USE_CMSIS_NN` is {{ "ON" if use_cmsis_nn else "OFF" }} for this target. When the fetched
executorch revision ships Cortex-M/CMSIS-NN kernels they are compiled in;
otherwise ops run on the portable reference kernels (correct but slower).
